) to match them up.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is a batch converter - <a href=\"http://atlas.dmi.unict.it/mirandola/tools.php\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://atlas.dmi.unict.it/mirandola/tools.php<\/a> - add the text list to box on the right and it produces a table.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7512,"question_id":7504,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1363160194}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7504/batch-convert-mirna-names-to-accession-ids","last_activity_date":1363160728,"creation_date":1363047840,"answer_count":2,"title":"Batch convert miRNA names to Accession IDs?","body":"<p>Does anyone know of tools to convert lists of miR names to their miRBase Accession IDs? I know they exist, but my search keeps pulling up gene ID converters.<\/p>\n\n<p>EDIT: both @rg255 and @shigeta have provided solutions to the underlying issue, but I am curious to know if something exists for miRNAs that is similar to a site like <a href=\"http://idconverter.bioinfo.cnio.es/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>EDIT 2: miRNA names are of the form 'hsa-let-7a' and Accession IDs are of the form 'MI0000060'<\/p>\n","question_id":7504,"tags":["bioinformatics"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":7512,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1231,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1363160728},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0bdc42625b0f249efa5990a64346e186?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3232,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3232/gpi","reputation":99,"display_name":"GPI","accept_rate":0},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/OxfyD.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3059,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3059/dd3","reputation":2303,"display_name":"dd3","accept_rate":95},"score":3,"post_id":7505,"edited":false,"creation_date":1363064720,"comment_id":9348,"body":"I wonder how much of this is because biologists have been taught statistical significance and haven&#39;t 