68/scott-stensland","reputation":178,"display_name":"Scott Stensland"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1362582378,"creation_date":1362582378,"body":"<p>Evolution works by tinkering, not engineering.  Gaining an evolutionary advantage in a simple way is rewarded, as is simplicity generally.  Symmetry allows for relatively greater simplicity at the genetic information level (modular body parts driven by repeated application of same genetic instructions).  Without symmetry, more genetic information would be needed to construct a similarly complex organism (symmetric like), with the concomitant exposure to increased genetic degradation.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7464,"question_id":7452,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7452/is-there-any-evolutionary-physiological-advantage-to-multi-lateral-symmetry","last_activity_date":1362582378,"creation_date":1362510160,"answer_count":2,"title":"Is there any evolutionary/physiological advantage to multi-lateral symmetry?","body":"<p>Just wondering ; I get the impression a large number of multicellular organisms are multi-lateral in their physical structure. Why would evolution/mutation have retained multi-lateral symmetry in an organism? What advantage/s does symmetry provide an organism?<\/p>\n\n<p>EDIT: \nBy multi-lateral symmetry I mean at-least bi-lateral symmetry (as in the case of many beings such as elephants, crabs and fishes), but perhaps more than bi-lateral too (starfish come to mind)<\/p>\n\n<p>END EDIT:<\/p>\n","question_id":7452,"tags":["evolution","physiology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":139,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1362539170},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"c