4881abfcbb1ff68abfc01a4108?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3189,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3189/darklighta","reputation":118,"display_name":"DarkLightA"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1362489147,"comment_id":9241,"body":"@DarkLightA Yes, that&#39;s probably around the number of neurons you have in total in your body. The actual pathway that a single signal will follow doesn&#39;t usually comprise that many cells though. Example: pain (e.g. papercut) -&gt; cell 1: sensory neuron from periphery (e.g. finger) towards spinal chord -&gt; cell 2: afferent neuron from spinal chord towards the thalamus in the brain -&gt; cell 3: thalamic neuron into various brain regions (exact number of cells here varies as far as I know) -&gt; result: you feel pain. Could be I forgot the odd neuron here or there in this pathway but that&#39;s the gist."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":0,"post_id":7432,"edited":false,"creation_date":1362489281,"comment_id":9242,"body":"The bit inside the brain could be quite a lot I think, hundreds or thousands even. Plus, a single stimulus doesn&#39;t activate just a single sensory neuron, and there are also cross-interactions of adjacent pathways."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1362421765,"creation_date":1362421327,"body":"<p>You've got a few things mixed up here:<\/p>\n\n<p>A <strong>signal<\/strong> may travel down a pathway, passing through several <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuron\">neurons<\/a> (e.g. around 4-8). However, this signal is not always in the same form: From one end of a neuron to the other, it is merely an <em><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_potential\">electric potential<\/a><\/em> which travels down the neuron's <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_membrane\">cell membrane<\/a> (from the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dendrite\">dendrite<\/a> to the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axon_hillock\">axon hillock<\/a>, where the cell decides whether to carry the signal on; if yes, a new potential is sparked to travel down the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axon\">axon<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p>When the potential reaches the end of a neuron, i.e. an axon terminal, it causes <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/exocytosis\">exocytosis<\/a> of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmitter\">neurotransmitter<\/a>. The signal has become <em>chemical<\/em> now. This diffuses through the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synapse\">synaptic cleft<\/a> to the next neuron, where it acts on <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion%20channel\">ion channels<\/a> in the membrane to cause a new electric potential.<\/p>\n\n<p>So the actual distance a neurotransmitter travels is only the distance between the two membranes at the synapse, i.e. the synaptic cleft. This is only about 20-40 nm wide, so it's fairly rapid :)<\/p>\n","answer_id":7432,"question_id":7430,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1362421765}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7430/does-one-neurotransmitter-travel-all-the-way-through-the-nervous-system","last_activity_date":1362421765,"creation_date":1362420130,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does one neurotransmitter travel all the way through the nervous system?","body":"<p>Nerve impulses of course go really fast, but the neurotransmitters have to travel through millions of nerves, so how can it go that fast?<\/p>\n\n<p>Is it a sort of relay with lots of neurotransmitters taking over at each nerve cell, or do the neurotransmitters go all the way from A to B?<\/p>\n","question_id":7430,"tags":["neuroscience","neurotransmitter"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1009,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":1,"post_id":7411,"edited":false,"creation_date":1362249449,"comment_id":9209,"body":"Not as far as I know, they <i>do<\/i> however open the frozen foodstuffs to infection. It is not a good idea to thaw and refreeze for that reason."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hpj4v.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3053,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3053/drosophila","reputation":1073,"display_name":"Drosophila","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1362360334,"creation_date":1362360334,"body":"<p>Repeated freeze-thaw has virtually no effect on macronutrients, such as proteins, lipids, and sugars, because these are broken down to their basic building blocks (such as amino acids and simple sugars) upon food digestion anyway. <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.deepdyve.com/lp/american-association-for-clinical-chemistry/effect-of-repeated-freezing-and-thawing-on-vitamins-and-hormones-in-6b3T0n2R70\" rel=\"nofollow\">According to this paper<\/a> freeze-thaw has no effect on micronutrients, such as vitamins, as well.  <\/p>\n\n<p>What affects nutritious quality is the <strong>length<\/strong> of time the food remains frozen. Most household freezers maintain a temperature of -20*C. At this temperature the food doesn't get spoiled by bacteria, but degradation of vitamins still occurs, albeit at a slower rate. This is critical for some unstable vitamins, such as vitamin A and C. But elements such as iron, calcium, zinc, and phosphorus are not affected at all. <\/p>\n\n<p>If you want to prevent vitamin degradation for a very long time, you need a freezer that maintains food at -80*C. This is only if you want to keep the food frozen for many months though. <\/p>\n","answer_id":7422,"question_id":7411,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7411/do-repeated-freeze-thaw-strip-nutrition-from-vegetables-food","last_activity_date":1362360334,"creation_date":1362248062,"answer_count":1,"title":"Do repeated freeze-thaw strip nutrition from vegetables/food?","body":"<p>For some inexplicable reason from the ladies in my extended family (even friends!) seem to believe that vegetables/food should be subjected to as few freeze/thaw cycles as possible. The rationale put forward is that each such cycle reduces nutrition (sp. nutritive?) value, and accelerates rot.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm sceptical; Do repeated (sp. repetitive?) freeze/thaw cycles strip nutrition from vegetables/food? <\/p>\n","question_id":7411,"tags":["nutrition"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":7422,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":99,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/tpN1L.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1827,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1827/cryptic-%e3%83%84","reputation":511,"display_name":"cryptic ツ","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/adba480f757d6888109043eab2374107?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1839,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1839/sviter","reputation":486,"display_name":"sviter"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rat