:9151,"body":"@GerganaVandova I didn&#39;t presume either that they did or didn&#39;t. In both cases it&#39;s still a probable reason for this problem. I imagine an ideal set of answers as all probable reasons for a problem. Then anyone looking this up in the future could use the answers to troubleshoot."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":0,"post_id":7358,"edited":false,"creation_date":1361890580,"comment_id":9157,"body":"Does this apply to very old models? How would the thermocycler test the volume in a tube or the temperature it reaches? We weren&#39;t using a hot start."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550973bfc1f6c08ff29efee9a1cc7fa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":2938,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2938/jack-aidley","reputation":3478,"display_name":"Jack Aidley"},"score":0,"post_id":7358,"edited":false,"creation_date":1361890967,"comment_id":9158,"body":"Older models simply raise the block to the temperature and don&#39;t worry about controlling for getting the liquid in the tube to the indicated temperature. In this case, it is possible that the real temperatures were different depending on volume."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":0,"post_id":7358,"edited":false,"creation_date":1361900449,"comment_id":9163,"body":"That sounds like the most likely problem; I think you should post that as an answer."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1361854837,"creation_date":1361854837,"body":"<p>The thermal cycler adjusts sample temperature based on the volume of the sample. So if you run samples of different volumes side by side, not all of them will cycle through the optimal temperatures of each step. If you were working with a \"hot start\" polymerase this is even more critical, as the Taq won't be able to amplify at all unless the sample is heated up to a specific temperature.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7358,"question_id":7356,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7356/effect-of-doubling-volumes-of-pcr-reagents","last_activity_date":1361891281,"creation_date":1361834874,"answer_count":1,"title":"Effect of doubling volumes of PCR reagents","body":"<p>We ran PCR with a positive control and two lanes of sample. We used the same sample, but in one PCR mixture we used a total volume of 50&mu;L (25&mu;L Taq, 5&mu;L forward&amp;reverse primer each, 10&mu;L sample, 5&mu;L dH2O) while in the other we halved each volume to a total of 25&mu;L. Pipetting was done by the same person.<\/p>\n\n<p>The positive control and the 25&mu;L total volume lane gave nice and clear bands, but the 50&mu;L sample showed nothing. How could this be explained?<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit: We only ran one PCR with all the samples simultaneously, so no second thermocycler or different temperatures or anything. Didn't even consider that option!<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit 2: In case it's relevant, we were using this: <a href=\"http://www.chemheritage.org/discover/collections/collection-items/scientific-instruments/perkin-elmer-cetus-model-480-dna-thermal-cycler.aspx\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.chemheritage.org/discover/collections/collection-items/scientific-instruments/perkin-elmer-cetus-model-480-dna-thermal-cycler.aspx<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":7356,"tags":["gel-electrophoresis","pcr","diy-biology"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":191,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1361891281},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/af238909cbe3042e2